{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1ddf89eb-0876-4131-ac7f-5cd37f479038","content":"`SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` only tells the page not to **add padding** for safe-area insets — it doesn't make the app draw behind the system bars. You likely need two more things:\n\n**1. Enable edge-to-edge on Android**\n\nIn your `MainActivity.cs` (or platform startup), opt in so the app draws behind the status/nav bars:\n\n```csharp\n// Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs\nprotected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)\n{\n    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);\n    AndroidX.Core.View.WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window!, false);\n}\n```\n\nOn .NET 10 targeting Android 15 (API 35+), this is the default — but on older API levels you must opt in.\n\n**2. Hide the app-level navigation bar**\n\nIf you're using `Shell` or `NavigationPage`, their chrome still takes space:\n\n```xml\n<!-- For Shell -->\n<ContentPage Shell.NavBarIsVisible=\"False\"\n             Shell.TabBarIsVisible=\"False\"\n             SafeAreaEdges=\"None\">\n\n<!-- For NavigationPage -->\n<ContentPage NavigationPage.HasNavigationBar=\"False\"\n             SafeAreaEdges=\"None\">\n```\n\n**3. Make the image fill the page**\n\n```xml\n<Image Source=\"photo.jpg\"\n       Aspect=\"AspectFill\"\n       HorizontalOptions=\"Fill\"\n       VerticalOptions=\"Fill\" />\n```\n\nWith all three in place, the image should render edge-to-edge behind both system bars.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0ca7f26c-dc77-4e8d-962b-37b0d341dd57","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about making an image go edge-to-edge in a .NET MAUI app, behind the status bar and navigation bar. They've tried `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on the ContentPage but the image still has padding.\n\nThis is about .NET MAUI's safe area and edge-to-edge display. Let me think about what's needed:\n\n1. In .NET MAUI, `SafeAreaEdges` is an iOS-specific concept that controls whether the page respects safe area insets.\n2. But to go truly edge-to-edge, you also need to handle Android's edge-to-edge display.\n\n\n3. On iOS, `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` should work, but on Android the approach differs depending on the API level—Android 15 and later have edge-to-edge by default, while earlier versions require opting in through the Window configuration.\n4. The `NavigationPage` or `Shell` might be adding its own padding that needs to be accounted for separately.\n5. The image or layout itself might also need properties adjusted to truly extend edge-to-edge.\n\nThe main things to check are Android's edge-to-edge configuration, iOS safe area handling, and whether the navigation bar is hiding properly. Let me think through what the user actually needs to implement. The Image also needs proper sizing with fill options and aspect ratio settings to stretch across the full screen.","outputTokens":1318,"requestId":"1030:16EA54:1617CB2:18C59E5:69FD36EE"},"id":"d10ddc96-4950-4e77-8daa-28826ee4a013","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:06:18.508Z","parentId":"776ced1f-957b-4f77-86cf-7c726fcbea29"}
